AMENDMENTS TO LB1096
Introduced by Judiciary.
1 1. Strike the original sections and insert the following new
2 sections:
3 Section 1. Sections 1 to 5 of this act shall be known and may be
4 cited as the Preventing Lethal Agricultural and National Threats Act.
5 Sec. 2. For purposes of the Preventing Lethal Agricultural and
6 National Threats Act:
7 (1) Department means the Department of Agriculture; and
8 (2) High-risk agricultural pathogen or pest means:
9 (a) Any disease or pest included in the list of diseases or pests of
10 concern, as such list existed on January 1, 2026, established by the
11 Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service of the United States
12 Department of Agriculture pursuant to 7 U.S.C. 8914; and
13 (b) Any agent, toxin, or organism designated under section 5 of this
14 act as a high-risk agricultural pathogen or pest.
15 Sec. 3. (1) Except as otherwise provided in this section, no person
16 shall:
17 (a) Knowingly import a high-risk agricultural pathogen or pest into
18 this state; or
19 (b) Import a high-risk agricultural pathogen or pest into this state
20 with a conscious disregard of a substantial or unjustifiable risk that
21 the high-risk agricultural pathogen or pest could cause significant harm
22 to crops, livestock, or agricultural ecosystems.
23 (2) A person may import a high-risk agricultural pathogen or pest
24 into this state if such person possesses a permit or authorization for
25 such importation from the department or the Animal and Plant Health
26 Inspection Service of the United States Department of Agriculture.
27 Sec. 4. (1) Except as otherwise provided in this section, a
-1-

AM2726 AM2726
LB1096 LB1096
JNH - 03/17/2026 JNH - 03/17/2026
1 violation of section 3 of this act is a Class III felony.
2 (2) A violation of section 3 of this act is a Class IIA felony if
3 the violation:
4 (a) Involves concealment of the origin of a high-risk agricultural
5 pathogen or pest;
6 (b) Is committed by a person acting on behalf of, or funded by, a
7 foreign government; or
8 (c) Results in actual economic damage exceeding one million dollars.
9 Sec. 5. (1) The department may adopt and promulgate rules and
10 regulations that designate any agent, toxin, or organism as a high-risk
11 agricultural pathogen or pest if such agent, toxin, or organism is
12 capable of causing significant harm to crops, livestock, or agricultural
13 ecosystems.
14 (2) The department may adopt and promulgate rules and regulations to
15 carry out the Preventing Lethal Agricultural and National Threats Act.
16 Sec. 6. (1) For purposes of this section:
17 (a) Company means a for-profit sole proprietorship, organization,
18 association, corporation, partnership, joint venture, limited
19 partnership, limited liability partnership, or limited liability company,
20 including a wholly owned subsidiary, majority owned subsidiary, parent
21 company, or affiliate of those entities or business associations that
22 exists to make a profit;
23 (b) Critical infrastructure means the 911 system, a communication
24 infrastructure system, a cybersecurity system, a high voltage electric
25 grid, a hazardous waste treatment system, or a water treatment facility;
26 (c) Cybersecurity means the measures taken to protect a computer,
27 computer network, computer system, or other technology infrastructure
28 against unauthorized use or access;
29 (d) Foreign adversary means those countries listed in 15 C.F.R.
30 791.4, as such regulation existed on January 1, 2026;
31 (e) Foreign principal means:
-2-

AM2726 AM2726
LB1096 LB1096
JNH - 03/17/2026 JNH - 03/17/2026
1 (i) The government or any official of the government of a foreign
2 adversary;
3 (ii) A political party of a foreign adversary or a member of such
4 political party or any subdivision of such political party;
5 (iii)(A) A partnership, an association, a corporation, an
6 organization, or any other combination of persons organized under the
7 laws of or having its principal place of business in a foreign adversary;
8 (B) A subsidiary of an entity described in subdivision (1)(e)(iii)
9 (A) of this section; or
10 (C) An entity owned or controlled wholly or in part by any person,
11 entity, or collection of persons or entities described in subdivision (1)
12 (e)(iii)(A) or (B) of this section;
13 (iv) Any person who is domiciled in a foreign adversary and is not a
14 citizen or lawful permanent resident of the United States; and
15 (v) Any person, entity, or collection of persons or entities
16 described in subdivisions (1)(e)(i) through (iv) of this section having a
17 controlling interest in a partnership, association, corporation,
18 organization, trust, or any other legal entity or subsidiary formed for
19 the purpose of owning real property; and
20 (f) Governmental entity means any agency, department, board,
21 commission, or political subdivision of the state that owns, operates,
22 manages, or provides oversight for critical infrastructure.
23 (2)(a) A company or other entity constructing, repairing, operating,
24 or otherwise having significant access to critical infrastructure shall
25 not knowingly enter into a contract or other agreement relating to
26 critical infrastructure in this state with a foreign principal if the
27 contract or other agreement would allow the foreign principal to directly
28 or remotely access or control critical infrastructure in this state.
29 (b) A governmental entity shall not knowingly enter into a contract
30 or other agreement relating to critical infrastructure in this state with
31 a company that is a foreign principal if the contract or other agreement
-3-

AM2726 AM2726
LB1096 LB1096
JNH - 03/17/2026 JNH - 03/17/2026
1 would allow the foreign principal to directly or remotely access or
2 control critical infrastructure in this state.
3 (c) Notwithstanding subdivisions (2)(a) and (b) of this section, a
4 company or other entity may enter into a contract or agreement relating
5 to critical infrastructure with a foreign principal if all of the
6 following apply:
7 (i) There is no other reasonable option for addressing the need
8 relevant to state critical infrastructure; and
9 (ii) Not entering into such contract or agreement would pose a
10 greater threat to the state than the threat associated with entering into
11 the contract.
